Cereal Volume 10 officially launches on 21 September and this issue will mark our 3 year anniversary

For this volume, we travelled to Northern California, Antwerp, and Panama City. In NorCal, we drive up the beautiful Route 1 to Big Sur; discuss modern winemaking with Scribe Winery; hike the fabled paths of Yosemite; examine the story of Levis Strauss; and show our readers what our ideal 24 hours in SF and Oakland looks like.&nbsp;

In Antwerp, we visit the headquarters of renowned interior designer Axel Vervoordt; interview celebrated fashion designer Dries Van Noten about his favourite spots in town; spend a day at Middelheim Sculpture Park; and investigate the legend associated with this Flemish city.

Over in Panama City, we wander the historic streets of Casco Viejo; take an aerial flight over the famous Panama Canal, and make our first jaunt into a jungle.&nbsp;

The interlude is our biggest yet, and here we examine the work of artist Agnes Martin as well as her retrospective at Tate Modern; explore invisible design with Vitsoe; tour the Swiss headquarters of master watchmakers Audemars Piguet; interview Copenhagen-based Norm Architects; present an edit of classic timepieces in CURATED; and style what we believe to be the ideal reading room.&nbsp;

In our literary supplement, WEEKEND, we write on the subject of ego, and interview the editor of The Gentlewoman, Penny Martin, on the topic.

Introducing the Entrepreneurs Issue.&nbsp;

For the Entrepreneurs Issue, we explore the motivation and innovation that drives the spirit of entrepreneurship in our workplaces, as well as provide inspiration to balance our regular workdays with more leisure time.

After all, we ire all budding entrepreneurs in one way or another, whether we own a small business, have grand plans for starting one or just enjoy daydreaming about throwing caution to the wind to make donuts full-time. Whether you ire working in an artistic field as a maker and doer, crunching numbers or saving lives, creativity can be found in all our pursuits.

While Kinfolk often focuses on the choices we make outside of work hours, this issue gives the same mindful attention to the time spent improving our professional selves. As mom would say, &ldquo;If you love what you do, you ill never have to work another day in your life.&rdquo;

Taking a simple, elegant &amp; understated approach, the single hand acts as both hour &amp; minute marker &ndash; with seconds consigned to history.&nbsp;

The face of the watch features 12 long tick marks denoting hours, with shorter marks denoting 15 minute segments and even shorter markers denoting 5-minute segments. The solitary hand therefore makes two full rotations per day, once in the morning &amp; once in the evening.&nbsp;

Despite being a little imprecise, it is still quick and simple way to tell what time it is within 5-minutes either way with nothing but a single glance.

